 for bestpractices and # Reminders & Notifications

## Overview
Implement a robust Reminders & Notifications system for QuestHabit that delivers scheduled reminders for habits via push notifications (FCM for Android/Web Push, APNs for iOS), with optional email fallback, and an in-app Notification Center. The system supports user-configurable channels (push, email), quiet hours, time zone-aware scheduling, retry/backoff strategies, and a server-side scheduler. UI components include a Notifications Center, Habit Detail, and Settings & Preferences pages. All code must defensively guard against null/undefined values for arrays and API results, and initialize React state with proper defaults for arrays/objects.

---

## Components to Build

1) Notifications Center (page_notifications)
- Purpose: In-app inbox listing all reminders, challenge updates, friend invites, and system messages.
- Data:
  - notifications: array of { id, type, title, message, timestamp, read, relatedHabitId?, meta }
  - types: reminder, challenge_update, friend_invite, system_message
- UI:
  - List with search, filter by type, mark all as read, bulk actions (delete/archive)
  - Card/list items with avatar/icon, title, snippet, timestamp, unread indicator
  - Pull-to-refresh / manual refresh
  - Detail view on click (quick preview, mark as read)
- Interactions:
  - Mark as read/unread, delete, filter, navigate to Habit Detail if relatedHabitId exists
  - Real-time or polling update placeholder (websocket/long-polling hook)

2) Habit Detail (page_habit_detail)
- Purpose: Show a single habit’s history, analytics, schedule, reminders, and editing shortcuts.
- Data:
  - habit: { id, name, color, schedule, timezone, reminders: [{ id, time, method, enabled }] }
  - history: array of { date, status }
  - analytics: usage metrics (streak, completion rate, average completion time)
- UI:
  - Header with habit name and quick edit actions
  - Tabs or sections: History, Analytics, Schedule, Reminders
  - Schedule editor (timezone-aware, multi-timezone support)
  - Reminders editor inline (add/edit/remove, enable/disable)
  - Shortcuts: quick edit, quick log, quick complete
- Interactions:
  - Add/modify reminder times (with correct time zone handling)
  - Edit habit metadata (name/color)
  - Visualizations: sparkline of activity, small bar charts for history

3) Settings & Preferences (page_settings)
- Purpose: Global notification and onboarding preferences, theme, sync settings, quiet hours, and channel configuration.
- Data:
  - userSettings: { pushEnabled, emailEnabled, quietHours: { start, end }, timezone, theme, onboardingCompleted, syncFrequency, preferredChannels: { push, email } }
- UI:
  - Sections: Notification Channels, Quiet Hours, Onboarding, Theme, Sync & Data
  - Toggles, time pickers, selectors
  - Save/Reset/Defaults with validation
- Interactions:
  - Enable/disable push/email channels
  - Configure quiet hours with validation (start < end, valid times)
  - Theme switch (light/dark/system)
  - Sync frequency options (auto, manual, interval)

4) Scheduler & Backend Services (server)
- Purpose: Centralized reminder scheduling, delivery, retries, and analytics.
- Data models:
  - UserReminders: { id, userId, habitId, timeOfDay (HH:mm), daysOfWeek[], timezone, channels: { push: true, email: false }, enabled, lastSentAt, nextTriggerAt, meta }
  - NotificationsLog: { id, userId, type, title, message, sentAt, status (delivered, failed, pending), error }
  - RemindersHistory: { id, reminderId, date, status, note }
  - UserSettings: { userId, pushToken, email, timezone, preferences }
- APIs/Functions:
  - scheduleReminders(userId, reminderSpec): create/update UserReminders, compute nextTriggerAt considering timezone
  - triggerReminders(): cron/queue worker to dispatch due reminders
  - deliverPush(user, payload): via FCM/APNs
  - sendEmail(user, subject, body): via SendGrid or alternative email service
  - retryBackoff(reminder): exponential backoff on failure
  - markAsDelivered(reminderId), markAsFailed(reminderId, error)
  - fetchNotificationsForUser(userId): returns Notification objects (for in-app center)
- Scheduling:
  - Timezone-aware: store timezone per user; compute nextTriggerAt in UTC
  - Recurrence: daily/weekday/weekend patterns, per-habit schedule
  - Quiet hours: suppress notifications outside window unless critical
- Security:
  - Validate user authentication/authorization for all endpoints
  - Rate limiting and idempotency keys for reminder delivery
- Data integrity:
  - Use null-safe access and guards: data ?? [], Array.isArray(data) checks, default objects

5) API Gateway / Endpoints
- RESTful routes (examples):
  - GET /api/users/{userId}/notifications?limit=&offset=&type=
  - POST /api/users/{userId}/notifications/mark-read
  - GET /api/habits/{habitId}
  - POST /api/users/{userId}/reminders
  - PUT /api/users/{userId}/reminders/{reminderId}
  - DELETE /api/users/{userId}/reminders/{reminderId}
  - POST /api/settings (update user preferences)
  - POST /api/scheduler/run-now (manual trigger for testing)
- Webhooks / Push receipts:
  - POST /api/push/callback to record delivery status
- Email:
  - Email templates via SendGrid with personalization tokens

6) Integration Layer
- Connecting frontend to backend via typed API clients (SDK)
- Push integration:
  - FCM: device tokens, topic subscriptions, platform-specific payloads
  - APNs: device tokens, push tokens
- Email fallback:
  - Triggered if push delivery fails after retry
  - Opt-in per user; respect quiet hours
- In-app center sync:
  - When a remote notification is delivered, create a corresponding in-app Notification entry
- Timezone handling:
  - All scheduling logic should store and compute times in UTC, convert to user timezone for display
- Data validation:
  - Validate all inputs; reject malformed reminder configurations
- Caching:
  - Cache user settings to minimize repeated DB reads; ensure cache invalidation on changes

---

## User Experience Flow

1) Onboarding
- User opens app; prompted to enable push notifications and optional email reminders
- User selects preferred channels and sets initial quiet hours
- Theme preference chosen (light/dark/system) and synced

2) Habit Setup
- User creates a habit with a schedule (e.g., daily at 09:00 local time)
- User configures reminders per habit (time, channels)
- System stores reminder rules with timezone and nextTriggerAt

3) Notification Delivery
- Scheduler runs at configured intervals, determines due reminders
- For each due reminder:
  - Send push notification via FCM/APNs if enabled
  - If push fails or is unavailable, and email enabled, send email
  - Create in-app Notification Center entry for the user
- On success, update lastSentAt/nextTriggerAt; on failure, apply exponential backoff and retry

4) In-app Notification Center
- User navigates to Notifications Center
- See list of reminders, challenge updates, invites, and system messages
- Mark as read, delete or archive
- Click items to navigate to related Habit Detail or other screens

5) Habit Detail Interaction
- Open Habit Detail to view history and analytics
- Add or edit reminders for that habit
- Access quick editing shortcuts to adjust schedule or mark as complete

6) Settings & Preferences
- User adjusts notification channels, quiet hours, onboarding prompts, theme, and sync
- Changes propagate to scheduler, and immediate effect on delivery

7) Ongoing Maintenance
- Retry/backoff handles transient failures
- Admins can monitor delivery metrics and adjust templates
- Users can manage notification preferences at any time

---

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models (schemas)
  - UserReminders: id, userId, habitId, timeOfDay, daysOfWeek[], timezone, channels { push, email }, enabled, nextTriggerAt, lastSentAt, metadata
  - NotificationsLog: id, userId, type, title, message, sentAt, status, error
  - Habits: id, userId, name, color, schedule, timezone, reminders[]
  - Users: id, email, pushToken, timezone, preferences
  - Settings: userId, theme, onboardingCompleted, quietHours { start, end }, syncFrequency, preferredChannels
- API Endpoints (examples)
  - GET /api/users/{userId}/notifications?limit=&offset=&type=
  - POST /api/users/{userId}/notifications/mark-read
  - GET /api/habits/{habitId}
  - POST /api/users/{userId}/reminders
  - PUT /api/users/{userId}/reminders/{reminderId}
  - DELETE /api/users/{userId}/reminders/{reminderId}
  - POST /api/settings
  - POST /api/scheduler/run-now
- Security
  - JWT or session-based auth; validate tokens on every request
  - Role-based access: user-scoped data; deny cross-user access
  - Input validation and strict type checks
  - Rate limiting on heavy endpoints
- Validation Rules
  - Time formats: HH:mm in 24h format; timezone strings valid
  - Days of week: array of valid values [ Sun, Mon, Tue, Wed, Thu, Fri, Sat ]
  - Reminder time must not overlap conflicting reminders for same habit
  - Enable/disable toggles require at least one channel if notifications are enabled
  - Quiet hours: start must be before end (with overnight support if needed)
- Frontend State Management
  - Use React with hooks or a state library
  - Initialize arrays with useState<Type[]>([]) and objects with appropriate defaults
  - Guard all array operations: (data ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(data) ? data.map(...) : []
  - Safely handle API results with: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- Integration
  - FCM/APNs: integrate with platform-specific push services; store device tokens per user
  - Email service: integrate with SendGrid or equivalent; templates per reminder type
  - Scheduler: server-side job queue (e.g., Bull, Agenda) or cron with idempotent delivery
  - Data flows between scheduler, push/email, and in-app notifications
  - Logging: persist delivery outcomes; expose dashboards for monitoring
- Accessibility
  - Ensure color contrast per palette; provide high-contrast mode if needed
  - Keyboard navigable controls; aria-labels on actionable items
- Performance
  - Debounce heavy UI actions; paginate notifications
  - Cache user settings and frequently accessed data with invalidation on updates
- Internationalization
  - Prepare strings for i18n; format times/dates per user locale

---

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Push notifications delivered via FCM for Android/Web Push and APNs for iOS when reminders are due, respecting user-chosen channels and quiet hours
- [ ] Email fallback reliably delivers reminders when push fails, with exponential backoff on repeated failures
- [ ] Server-side scheduler calculates nextTriggerAt accurately based on user timezone and habit schedule
- [ ] In-app Notifications Center displays all message types (reminders, challenge updates, friend invites, system messages) and supports read/unread state, filtering, and search
- [ ] Habit Detail page shows history, analytics, schedule, and per-habit reminders with real-time editing capabilities
- [ ] Settings & Preferences allow configuring channels, quiet hours, onboarding prompts, theme, and sync settings; changes persist and immediately affect delivery
- [ ] All API responses validated; data accessed with null-safe guards; arrays initialized as [] and objects with defaults
- [ ] UI adheres to the project’s design system, with accessible colors, typography, and responsive layout
- [ ] Comprehensive tests:
  - Unit tests for scheduling logic and reminder calculation
  - Integration tests for end-to-end delivery flow (mocked push/email)
  - UI tests for Notifications Center filtering/search and Habit Detail reminder editing

---

## UI/UX Guidelines

Apply QuestHabit’s design system consistently across all components:

- Visual Style:
  - Color usage strictly follows the provided palette (orange #FF9A57 as primary, violet #7C61FF as secondary)
  - Soft peach-cream backgrounds with frosted-glass card aesthetics
  - Dark mode surfaces with near-black cards for emphasis
  - Subtle gradients (warm gradient #FF9A57 → #FFD7A8; purple gradient #7C61FF → #BFA7FF)
  - Elevations via soft shadows; minimal drop shadows for depth; glow used sparingly for celebratory states
- Typography:
  - Poppins/Inter-like rounded geometric sans
  - h1 700, h2 600, body 400, labels 500, numeric 700
  - Mobile typography targets: Title 20–24px, Subhead 16–18px, Body 14–15px, Caption 12px
- Layout:
  - Single-column vertical flow with stacked cards; bottom navigation with center FAB for new reminder
  - 8px grid multiples; 16–24px card padding; generous horizontal padding on mobile (16–20px)
- Components:
  - Cards: full-width with 16–24px corner radii; frosted glass effect on light surfaces
  - Buttons: primary pill with warm gradient; secondary outlined pills
  - Inputs: rounded rectangles with clear focus rings in purple
  - Charts: rounded bars with gradients; sparklines where space allows
  - Micro-interactions: subtle animations for hover/press; confetti for achievements
- Accessibility:
  - Sufficient color contrast; ARIA labels; keyboard accessible; option to adjust animation intensity if available

---

## Visual Style Reference (Key Tokens)

- Primary: #FF9A57 (orange), #FFD7A8 (gradient end)
- Secondary: #7C61FF (violet), #BFA7FF (gradient end)
- Text: #0F1724 (primary), #6B7280 (secondary), #9AA0A6 (muted)
- Backgrounds: #FFF4EA (base), #F7E1C9 (gradient stop), #FFF7F0 (cards)
- Dark: #11121A (cards), #0F1724 (text contrasts)
- Accents/Info: #4AB3FF (sky blue), #54D8A9 (mint), #BFA7FF (lavender)
- Gradients:
  - Warm: linear-gradient(#FF9A57, #FFD7A8)
  - Purple: linear-gradient(#7C61FF, #BFA7FF)
- Shadows: rgba(15,17,36,0.06)

---

## Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety

CRITICAL: Implement all code with runtime safety in mind.

- Supabase-like results handling:
  - const items = data ?? []
  - Guard arrays: Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
- API responses:
  - const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- React state initialization:
  - useState<Type[]>([]) for arrays; useState<Type>({} as Type) for objects if needed
- Optional chaining and defaults:
  - const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}
  - Access nested properties safely: obj?.property?.nested
- Validation:
  - Validate inputs server-side and client-side
  - Validate time formats and timezone strings
- Null safety:
  - Never call .map/.filter/.reduce on undefined/null without guards

---

